<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1895-06-06T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1895-06-06T00:00:00-05:00" n="414" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d414">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Eustis</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">Uhl</persName></hi>.</head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Embassy
                                        of the United States</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Paris</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1895-06-06"><hi rend="italic">June 6, 1895</hi></date>.
                                (Received June 17.)</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 311.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Yesterday I had an interview with Mr.
                            Hanotaux and followed the instructions of your dispatch No. 424, of May
                            23, in reference to the Venezuelan affair.</p>
                        <pb facs="0484" n="424" xml:id="pg_424"/>
                        <p>He accepted my official statement with courtesy, but gave me no
                            encouragement to believe that the French Government would change its
                            attitude.</p>
                        <p>I have, etc.,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">J. B. Eustis</hi></signed>.</closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>